  "response_text": "The aggregate count of milk selections begins at zero and accumulates at a constant rate of approximately 1,000 decisions per time step throughout the simulation period. By the conclusion of the 31-year timeframe, the total number of choices made reaches roughly 32,000. This linear accumulation pattern indicates that each of the 1,000 agents participates in the decision-making process exactly once per time step, with no variation in participation rates, agent dropout, or entry of new consumers over the duration of the simulation. The consistency of this trend suggests that the model maintains a stable population structure where every agent is required to make a milk selection at each discrete time interval, reflecting a uniform temporal rhythm of consumption decisions across the entire virtual marketplace."
}

